28using Block = BigInteger::Block;
29using Magnitude = std::vector<Block>;
30
31static const size_t NB_BITS = 8 * sizeof(Block);
32
33static void AddMag(const Magnitude& a, const Magnitude& b, Magnitude& c)
34{
35 // a2 points to the longer input, b2 points to the shorter
36 const Magnitude& a2 = a.size() >= b.size() ? a : b;
37 const Magnitude& b2 = a.size() >= b.size() ? b : a;
38
39 // need to store the old sizes of a and b, in case c aliases either of them
40 const size_t a2Size = a2.size(), b2Size = b2.size();
41
42 c.resize(a2Size + 1);
43 size_t i = 0;
44 bool carryIn = false;
45 for (; i < b2Size; ++i) {
46 auto temp = a2[i] + b2[i];
47 bool carryOut = (temp < a2[i]);
48 if (carryIn) {
49 ++temp;
50 carryOut |= (temp == 0);
51 }
52 c[i] = temp;
53 carryIn = carryOut;
54 }
55 // If there is a carry left over, increase blocks until one does not roll over.
56 for (; i < a2Size && carryIn; ++i) {
57 auto temp = a2[i] + 1;
58 carryIn = (temp == 0);
59 c[i] = temp;
60 }
61 // If the carry was resolved but the larger number still has blocks, copy them over.
62 for (; i < a2Size; ++i) {
63 c[i] = a2[i];
64 }
65 // Set the extra block if there's still a carry, decrease length otherwise
66 if (carryIn) {
67 c[i] = 1;
68 }
69 else {
70 c.pop_back();
71 }
72}
73
74// Note that we DO NOT support the case where b is greater than a.
75static void SubMag(const Magnitude& a, const Magnitude& b, Magnitude& c)
76{
77 assert(a.size() >= b.size());
78
79 // need to store the old sizes of a and b, in case c aliases either of them
80 const size_t aSize = a.size(), bSize = b.size();
81
82 c.resize(aSize);
83 size_t i = 0;
84 bool borrowIn = false;
85 for (; i < bSize; ++i) {
86 auto temp = a[i] - b[i];
87 // If a reverse rollover occurred, the result is greater than the block from a.
88 bool borrowOut = (temp > a[i]);
89 if (borrowIn) {
90 borrowOut |= (temp == 0);
91 temp--;
92 }
93 c[i] = temp;
94 borrowIn = borrowOut;
95 }
96 // If there is a borrow left over, decrease blocks until one does not reverse rollover.
97 for (; i < aSize && borrowIn; ++i) {
98 borrowIn = (a[i] == 0);
99 c[i] = a[i] - 1;
100 }
101 //if (borrowIn) {
102 //throw error;
103 //}
104 // Copy over the rest of the blocks
105 for (; i < aSize; ++i) {
106 c[i] = a[i];
107 }
108
109 // Zap leading zeros
110 while (!c.empty() && c.back() == 0) {
111 c.pop_back();
112 }
113}
114
115static inline Block GetShiftedBlock(const Magnitude& num, size_t x, size_t y)
116{
117 Block part1 = (x == 0 || y == 0) ? Block(0) : (num[x - 1] >> (NB_BITS - y));
118 Block part2 = (x == num.size()) ? Block(0) : (num[x] << y);
119 return part1 | part2;
120}
121
122static void MulMag(const Magnitude& a, const Magnitude& b, Magnitude& c)
123{
124 // If either a or b is zero, set to zero.
125 if (a.empty() || b.empty()) {
126 c.clear();
127 return;
128 }
129
130 Magnitude tmp;
131 Magnitude& r = &c == &a || &c == &b ? tmp : c;
132
133 /*
134 * Overall method:
135 *
136 * Set this = 0.
137 * For each 1-bit of `a' (say the `i2'th bit of block `i'):
138 * Add `b << (i blocks and i2 bits)' to *this.
139 */
140
141 r.clear();
142 r.resize(a.size() + b.size(), 0);
143
144 // For each block of the first number...
145 for (size_t i = 0; i < a.size(); ++i) {
146 // For each 1-bit of that block...
147 for (size_t i2 = 0; i2 < NB_BITS; ++i2) {
148 if ((a[i] & (Block(1) << i2)) == 0)
149 continue;
150 /*
151 * Add b to this, shifted left i blocks and i2 bits.
152 * j is the index in b, and k = i + j is the index in this.
153 *
154 * `getShiftedBlock', a short inline function defined above,
155 * is now used for the bit handling. It replaces the more
156 * complex `bHigh' code, in which each run of the loop dealt
157 * immediately with the low bits and saved the high bits to
158 * be picked up next time. The last run of the loop used to
159 * leave leftover high bits, which were handled separately.
160 * Instead, this loop runs an additional time with j == b.len.
161 * These changes were made on 2005.01.11.
162 */
163 size_t k = i;
164 bool carryIn = false;
165 for (size_t j = 0; j <= b.size(); ++j, ++k) {
166 /*
167 * The body of this loop is very similar to the body of the first loop
168 * in `add', except that this loop does a `+=' instead of a `+'.
169 */
170 auto temp = r[k] + GetShiftedBlock(b, j, i2);
171 auto carryOut = (temp < r[k]);
172 if (carryIn) {
173 temp++;
174 carryOut |= (temp == 0);
175 }
176 r[k] = temp;
177 carryIn = carryOut;
178 }
179 // No more extra iteration to deal with `bHigh'.
180 // Roll-over a carry as necessary.
181 for (; carryIn; k++) {
182 r[k]++;
183 carryIn = (r[k] == 0);
184 }
185 }
186 }
187 // Zap possible leading zero
188 if (r.back() == 0) {
189 r.pop_back();
190 }
191
192 if (&c != &r)
193 c = std::move(r);
194}

196/*
197* DIVISION WITH REMAINDER
198* This monstrous function mods *this by the given divisor b while storing the
199* quotient in the given object q; at the end, *this contains the remainder.
200* The seemingly bizarre pattern of inputs and outputs was chosen so that the
201* function copies as little as possible (since it is implemented by repeated
202* subtraction of multiples of b from *this).
203*
204* "modWithQuotient" might be a better name for this function, but I would
205* rather not change the name now.
206*/
207static void DivideWithRemainder(const Magnitude& a, const Magnitude& b, Magnitude& qq, Magnitude& rr)
208{
209 /* Defending against aliased calls is more complex than usual because we
210 * are writing to both r and q.
211 *
212 * It would be silly to try to write quotient and remainder to the
213 * same variable. Rule that out right away. */
214 assert(&rr != &qq);
215
216 Magnitude tmp, tmp2;
217 Magnitude& q = &qq == &a || &qq == &b ? tmp : qq;
218 Magnitude& r = &rr == &b ? tmp2 : rr;
219
220 /*
221 * Knuth's definition of mod (which this function uses) is somewhat
222 * different from the C++ definition of % in case of division by 0.
223 *
224 * We let a / 0 == 0 (it doesn't matter much) and a % 0 == a, no
225 * exceptions thrown. This allows us to preserve both Knuth's demand
226 * that a mod 0 == a and the useful property that
227 * (a / b) * b + (a % b) == a.
228 */
229 /*
230 * If a.len < b.len, then a < b, and we can be sure that b doesn't go into
231 * a at all. The quotient is 0 and *this is already the remainder (so leave it alone).
232 */
233 if (b.empty() || a.size() < b.size()) {
234 qq.clear();
235 rr = a;
236 return;
237 }
238
239 // At this point we know a.len >= b.len > 0. (Whew!)
240
241 /*
242 * Overall method:
243 *
244 * For each appropriate i and i2, decreasing:
245 * Subtract (b << (i blocks and i2 bits)) from *this, storing the
246 * result in subtractBuf.
247 * If the subtraction succeeds with a nonnegative result:
248 * Turn on bit i2 of block i of the quotient q.
249 * Copy subtractBuf back into *this.
250 * Otherwise bit i2 of block i remains off, and *this is unchanged.
251 *
252 * Eventually q will contain the entire quotient, and *this will
253 * be left with the remainder.
254 *
255 * subtractBuf[x] corresponds to blk[x], not blk[x+i], since 2005.01.11.
256 * But on a single iteration, we don't touch the i lowest blocks of blk
257 * (and don't use those of subtractBuf) because these blocks are
258 * unaffected by the subtraction: we are subtracting
259 * (b << (i blocks and i2 bits)), which ends in at least `i' zero
260 * blocks. */
261
262 /*
263 * Make sure we have an extra zero block just past the value.
264 *
265 * When we attempt a subtraction, we might shift `b' so
266 * its first block begins a few bits left of the dividend,
267 * and then we'll try to compare these extra bits with
268 * a nonexistent block to the left of the dividend. The
269 * extra zero block ensures sensible behavior; we need
270 * an extra block in `subtractBuf' for exactly the same reason.
271 */
272 if (&r != &a) {
273 r.reserve(a.size() + 1);
274 r = a;
275 }
276 r.push_back(0);
277
278 Magnitude subtractBuf(r.size());
279
280 // Set preliminary length for quotient and make room
281 q.resize(a.size() - b.size() + 1);
282
283 // For each possible left-shift of b in blocks...
284 size_t i = q.size();
285 while (i > 0) {
286 i--;
287 // For each possible left-shift of b in bits...
288 // (Remember, N is the number of bits in a Blk.)
289 q[i] = 0;
290 size_t i2 = NB_BITS;
291 while (i2 > 0) {
292 i2--;
293 /*
294 * Subtract b, shifted left i blocks and i2 bits, from *this,
295 * and store the answer in subtractBuf. In the for loop, `k == i + j'.
296 *
297 * Compare this to the middle section of `multiply'. They
298 * are in many ways analogous. See especially the discussion
299 * of `getShiftedBlock'.
300 */
301 size_t k = i;
302 bool borrowIn = false;
303 for (size_t j = 0; j <= b.size(); ++j, ++k) {
304 auto temp = r[k] - GetShiftedBlock(b, j, i2);
305 bool borrowOut = (temp > r[k]);
306 if (borrowIn) {
307 borrowOut |= (temp == 0);
308 temp--;
309 }
310 // Since 2005.01.11, indices of `subtractBuf' directly match those of `blk', so use `k'.
311 subtractBuf[k] = temp;
312 borrowIn = borrowOut;
313 }
314 // No more extra iteration to deal with `bHigh'.
315 // Roll-over a borrow as necessary.
316 for (; k < a.size() && borrowIn; k++) {
317 borrowIn = (r[k] == 0);
318 subtractBuf[k] = r[k] - 1;
319 }
320 /*
321 * If the subtraction was performed successfully (!borrowIn),
322 * set bit i2 in block i of the quotient.
323 *
324 * Then, copy the portion of subtractBuf filled by the subtraction
325 * back to *this. This portion starts with block i and ends--
326 * where? Not necessarily at block `i + b.len'! Well, we
327 * increased k every time we saved a block into subtractBuf, so
328 * the region of subtractBuf we copy is just [i, k).
329 */
330 if (!borrowIn) {
331 q[i] |= (Block(1) << i2);
332 while (k > i) {
333 k--;
334 r[k] = subtractBuf[k];
335 }
336 }
337 }
338 }
339 // Zap possible leading zero in quotient
340 if (q.back() == 0)
341 q.pop_back();
342
343 // Zap any/all leading zeros in remainder
344 while (!r.empty() && r.back() == 0) {
345 r.pop_back();
346 }
347
348 if (&qq != &q)
349 qq = std::move(q);
350 if (&rr != &r)
351 rr = std::move(r);
352}
353
354static int CompareMag(const Magnitude& a, const Magnitude& b)
355{
356 // A bigger length implies a bigger number.
357 if (a.size() < b.size()) {
358 return -1;
359 }
360 else if (a.size() > b.size()) {
361 return 1;
362 }
363 else {
364 // Compare blocks one by one from left to right.
365 auto p = std::mismatch(a.rbegin(), a.rend(), b.rbegin());
366 if (p.first != a.rend()) {
367 return *p.first < *p.second ? -1 : 1; // note: cannot use substraction here
368 }
369 return 0;
370 }
371}
372
373template <typename StrT>
374static bool ParseFromString(const StrT& str, std::vector<Block>& mag, bool& negative)
375{
376 auto iter = str.begin();
377 auto end = str.end();
378 while (iter != end && std::isspace(*iter)) ++iter;
379 if (iter != end) {
380 mag.clear();
381 negative = false;
382 if (*iter == '-') {
383 negative = true;
384 ++iter;
385 }
386 else if (*iter == '+') {
387 ++iter;
388 }
389
390 Magnitude ten{10};
391 Magnitude tmp{0};
392 for (int c; iter != end && std::isdigit(c = *iter); ++iter) {
393 tmp[0] = c - '0';
394 MulMag(mag, ten, mag);
395 AddMag(mag, tmp, mag);
396 }
397 return !mag.empty();
398 }
399 return false;
400}
401
402bool
403BigInteger::TryParse(const std::string& str, BigInteger& result)
404{
405 return ParseFromString(str, result.mag, result.negative);
406}
407
408bool
409BigInteger::TryParse(const std::wstring& str, BigInteger& result)
410{
411 return ParseFromString(str, result.mag, result.negative);
412}
413
414void
415BigInteger::Add(const BigInteger& a, const BigInteger &b, BigInteger& c)
416{
417 // If one argument is zero, copy the other.
418 if (a.mag.empty()) {
419 c = b;
420 return;
421 }
422 if (b.mag.empty()) {
423 c = a;
424 return;
425 }
426
427 // If the arguments have the same sign, take the
428 // common sign and add their magnitudes.
429 if (a.negative == b.negative) {
430 c.negative = a.negative;
431 AddMag(a.mag, b.mag, c.mag);
432 }
433 else {
434 // Otherwise, their magnitudes must be compared.
435 int cmp = CompareMag(a.mag, b.mag);
436 if (cmp < 0) {
437 c.negative = b.negative;
438 SubMag(b.mag, a.mag, c.mag);
439 }
440 else if (cmp > 0) {
441 c.negative = a.negative;
442 SubMag(a.mag, b.mag, c.mag);
443 }
444 else {
445 c.negative = false;
446 c.mag.clear();
447 }
448 }
449}
450
451void
452BigInteger::Subtract(const BigInteger &a, const BigInteger &b, BigInteger& c)
453{
454 if (a.mag.empty()) {
455 c.negative = !b.negative;
456 c.mag = b.mag;
457 return;
458 }
459 if (b.mag.empty()) {
460 c = a;
461 return;
462 }
463
464 // If their signs differ, take a.sign and add the magnitudes.
465 if (a.negative != b.negative) {
466 c.negative = a.negative;
467 AddMag(a.mag, b.mag, c.mag);
468 }
469 else {
470 int cmp = CompareMag(a.mag, b.mag);
471 if (cmp < 0) {
472 c.negative = !b.negative;
473 SubMag(b.mag, a.mag, c.mag);
474 }
475 else if (cmp > 0) {
476 c.negative = a.negative;
477 SubMag(a.mag, b.mag, c.mag);
478 }
479 else {
480 c.negative = false;
481 c.mag.clear();
482 }
483 }
484}
485
486void
487BigInteger::Multiply(const BigInteger &a, const BigInteger &b, BigInteger& c)
488{
489 if (a.mag.empty() || b.mag.empty()) {
490 c.negative = false;
491 c.mag.clear();
492 return;
493 }
494 c.negative = a.negative != b.negative;
495 MulMag(a.mag, b.mag, c.mag);
496}

499/*
500* DIVISION WITH REMAINDER
501* Please read the comments before the definition of
502* `BigUnsigned::divideWithRemainder' in `BigUnsigned.cc' for lots of
503* information you should know before reading this function.
504*
505* Following Knuth, I decree that x / y is to be
506* 0 if y==0 and floor(real-number x / y) if y!=0.
507* Then x % y shall be x - y*(integer x / y).
508*
509* Note that x = y * (x / y) + (x % y) always holds.
510* In addition, (x % y) is from 0 to y - 1 if y > 0,
511* and from -(|y| - 1) to 0 if y < 0. (x % y) = x if y = 0.
512*
513* Examples: (q = a / b, r = a % b)
514* a b q r
515* === === === ===
516* 4 3 1 1
517* -4 3 -2 2
518* 4 -3 -2 -2
519* -4 -3 1 -1
520*/
521void
522BigInteger::Divide(const BigInteger &a, const BigInteger &b, BigInteger &quotient, BigInteger& remainder)
523{
524 if (b.mag.empty() || a.mag.size() < b.mag.size()) {
525 quotient.mag.clear();
526 quotient.negative = false;
527 remainder = a;
528 return;
529 }
530
531 // Do the operands have the same sign?
532 if (a.negative == b.negative) {
533 // Yes: easy case. Quotient is zero or positive.
534 quotient.negative = false;
535 DivideWithRemainder(a.mag, b.mag, quotient.mag, remainder.mag);
536 }
537 else {
538 // No: harder case. Quotient is negative.
539 quotient.negative = true;
540 // Decrease the magnitude of the dividend by one.
541 Magnitude one{ 1 };
542 Magnitude aa;
543 SubMag(a.mag, one, aa);
544 /*
545 * We tinker with the dividend before and with the
546 * quotient and remainder after so that the result
547 * comes out right. To see why it works, consider the following
548 * list of examples, where A is the magnitude-decreased
549 * a, Q and R are the results of BigUnsigned division
550 * with remainder on A and |b|, and q and r are the
551 * final results we want:
552 *
553 * a A b Q R q r
554 * -3 -2 3 0 2 -1 0
555 * -4 -3 3 1 0 -2 2
556 * -5 -4 3 1 1 -2 1
557 * -6 -5 3 1 2 -2 0
558 *
559 * It appears that we need a total of 3 corrections:
560 * Decrease the magnitude of a to get A. Increase the
561 * magnitude of Q to get q (and make it negative).
562 * Find r = (b - 1) - R and give it the desired sign.
563 */
564 DivideWithRemainder(aa, b.mag, quotient.mag, remainder.mag);
565
566 AddMag(quotient.mag, one, quotient.mag);
567 // Modify the remainder.
568 SubMag(b.mag, remainder.mag, remainder.mag);
569 SubMag(remainder.mag, one, remainder.mag);
570 }
571
572 // Sign of the remainder is always the sign of the divisor b.
573 remainder.negative = b.negative;
574
575 // Set signs to zero as necessary. (Thanks David Allen!)
576 if (remainder.mag.empty())
577 remainder.negative = false;
578 if (quotient.mag.empty())
579 quotient.negative = false;
580}
581
582size_t ceilingDiv(size_t a, size_t b) {
583 return (a + b - 1) / b;
584}
585
586std::string
587BigInteger::toString() const
588{
589 if (mag.empty()) {
590 return "0";
591 }
592 std::string result;
593 if (negative) {
594 result.push_back('-');
595 }
596
597 static const uint32_t base = 10;
598 auto maxBitLenOfX = static_cast<uint32_t>(mag.size()) * NB_BITS;
599 int minBitsPerDigit = BitHacks::HighestBitSet(base);
600 auto maxDigitLenOfX = (maxBitLenOfX + minBitsPerDigit - 1) / minBitsPerDigit; // ceilingDiv
601
602 std::vector<uint8_t> buffer;
603 buffer.reserve(maxDigitLenOfX);
604
605 Magnitude x2 = mag;
606 Magnitude buBase{base};
607 Magnitude lastDigit;
608 lastDigit.reserve(1);
609
610 while (!x2.empty()) {
611 // Get last digit. This is like `lastDigit = x2 % buBase, x2 /= buBase'.
612 DivideWithRemainder(x2, buBase, x2, lastDigit);
613 // Save the digit.
614 buffer.push_back(static_cast<uint8_t>(lastDigit.empty() ? 0 : lastDigit.front()));
615 }
616
617 size_t offset = result.size();
618 result.resize(offset + buffer.size());
619 std::transform(buffer.rbegin(), buffer.rend(), result.begin() + offset, [](uint8_t c) { return static_cast<char>('0' + c); });
620 return result;
621}
622
623int
624BigInteger::toInt() const
625{
626 if (mag.empty())
627 return 0;
628 else if (negative)
629 return -static_cast<int>(mag.back());
630 else
631 return static_cast<int>(mag.back());
632}
